'''Vartnov castle''' is a ruined castle nearly {{convert|6|km|mi|0}} south of the town of [[Krnov]], [[Czech Republic]].

==History==
The castle was built in 14th century and is associated with the lords of Wartna. Supposedly in 1349 the castle changed its possessors and it was kept by Vok z Holštejna. His son Štěpán I. was already named by this castle as Štěpán I. z Vartnova. The first written reference is dated to 1377, when the partition of the [[Duchy of Troppau]] between the sons of the recently dead duke [[Nicholas II, Duke of Troppau|Nicholas II]] took place. Vartnovs domain devolved into part of [[John I, Duke of Opava-Ratibor|John I of Ratiborz]]. In 1421 the domain was sold to [[John II, Duke of Opava-Ratibor|John II of Ratiborz]]. The [[Duchy of Racibórz|Dukes of Raciborz]] possessed the castle until 1447, when it was granted by duke [[Nicholas V]] to his loyal servant Bernard Bírka z Násile. In 1474 during the war between [[Kingdom of Bohemia|Bohemia]] and [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungary]] the castle was conquered and burned to ashes. It was never rebuilt.

